  "signature": "ed25519:7c3a9f2d1e4b6a8c5f0d3e2b9a7f4c1d8e5b2a6f3c9d7e4b2a1f8c5d3e6b9a4c7",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/sqa-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R1) is a commercially validated code with documented version control, regression testing suite, and traceable release notes. All simulation input files are stored under Git version control with commit hashes recorded in the simulation log. Software qualification documentation confirms Gradation 2 requirements are satisfied: source code access is not required at MRL 2, and the commercial solver's validation history for blood pump flows is documented in the solver vendor's V&V reports."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/code-verification-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions (MMS) for the Navier-Stokes solver on canonical benchmark cases (lid-driven cavity, pipe flow with analytical solution). Second-order spatial convergence was confirmed. The turbulence model (SST k-omega) was verified against published benchmark results from the ERCOFTAC database. All verification cases passed with residuals below 1e-6. Gradation 2 is achieved: the solver is verified for the class of flow physics relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/discretization-error-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "A mesh refinement study was conducted using three mesh levels (coarse: 1.2M cells, medium: 3.8M cells, fine: 9.6M cells). The Grid Convergence Index (GCI) was computed for the relative hemolysis index QoI. The observed order of convergence was p=1.4 (below theoretical second-order), and the GCI for the fine-to-medium ratio was 8.3%, exceeding the 5% threshold required for Gradation 3. Richardson extrapolation indicates the solution has not fully entered the asymptotic convergence regime. Although the medium mesh was used for all production runs, the insufficient asymptotic convergence evidence means only Gradation 2 can be claimed. Required level is 3 (MRL 2, high decision consequence, hemolysis QoI sensitive to near-wall resolution). This factor does NOT meet the required level and is the primary basis for the Not Accepted decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/test-conditions-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions used for validation were conducted under controlled laboratory conditions matching the intended CPB operating envelope. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water mixture with matched viscosity at 37°C) was used. Flow rates spanning 2–6 L/min and rotational speeds of 2000–3500 RPM were tested, encompassing all 5 COU operating points. Temperature, inlet pressure, and outlet resistance were monitored and recorded with calibrated instrumentation (NIST-traceable). Test conditions are well-characterized and documented in the experimental test report TR-2024-CPB-001, exceeding Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison between CFD predictions and experimental measurements was performed using the relative hemolysis index (RH) and pump pressure head at all 5 operating points. The normalized index of agreement (d=0.87) and mean absolute error (MAE=6.2% for pressure head, 11.4% for RH) were computed. Experimental uncertainty bands were propagated from measurement uncertainty (±3% flow rate, ±0.5% pressure). CFD predictions fall within experimental uncertainty for 4 of 5 operating points for pressure head, and 3 of 5 for RH. This level of agreement supports Gradation 2 for output comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index (RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate), which directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1). Secondary QoIs include pump pressure head and wall shear stress distribution. The RH index is the standard metric used in FDA guidance for hemolysis assessment of blood-contacting devices and is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of red blood cell damage. The QoI selection is well-justified and documented in the modeling report MR-2024-CPB-001, exceeding Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl2-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same geometry class as the COU device. Operating conditions in validation experiments span the COU operating envelope. The blood analog fluid provides a reasonable surrogate for whole blood at the relevant shear rates. Differences between validation and COU conditions (blood analog vs. whole blood, in vitro vs. in vivo pressure environment) are documented and assessed as acceptable for Gradation 2, given that the primary hemolysis mechanism (mechanical shear) is captured by the analog fluid at matched viscosity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2 with medium model influence, Gradation 1 is required for numerical solver error beyond discretization. The commercial solver's iterative convergence was monitored: all residuals dropped below 1e-5 and mass imbalance was below 0.01%. Round-off error is negligible for double-precision arithmetic at this problem scale. No evidence of solver instability was observed. Scoped out from detailed assessment as the commercial solver's internal error control mechanisms are documented in vendor V&V reports and residual monitoring confirms acceptable solver performance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, Gradation 1 for use error is satisfied by documented simulation workflow with peer review. All boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and solver settings were reviewed by a second qualified engineer prior to production runs. Simulation setup checklist (Form QA-CFD-2024-07) was completed and signed. Scoped out from detailed assessment as the peer-review process and documented checklist provide sufficient assurance at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model and the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model are industry-standard choices for CFD hemolysis prediction in centrifugal blood pumps, with documented use in FDA-reviewed submissions. Model form uncertainty is acknowledged but not formally quantified at MRL 2 with Gradation 1 requirement. Literature evidence supporting model form adequacy for this class of flow is cited in the modeling report (MR-2024-CPB-001, Section 4.2). Scoped out from formal model form uncertainty quantification, consistent with MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Key model inputs (fluid viscosity, density, pump geometry dimensions, rotational speed, inlet flow rate) are well-characterized from manufacturer specifications and laboratory measurements. Nominal values with documented uncertainty ranges are tabulated in the modeling report. Sensitivity of RH to input variations was assessed qualitatively and found to be dominated by rotational speed and flow rate, both of which are controlled to within ±1% in the simulation. Scoped out from formal uncertainty propagation at MRL 2 Gradation 1, consistent with the risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Experimental validation data were obtained from three replicate test runs at each of the 5 operating points using the same pump specimen. Sample-to-sample variability was assessed from the replicates (CV < 4% for RH measurements). A single pump specimen was used, consistent with Gradation 1 requirements at MRL 2. Lot-to-lot manufacturing variability is not assessed at this gradation level. Scoped out from multi-specimen statistical assessment, documented as acceptable at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The mapping between experimental boundary conditions and CFD boundary conditions was verified: inlet flow rates, outlet pressure, rotational speed, and fluid properties in the simulation match the experimental test conditions within measurement uncertainty. Differences in inlet velocity profile (uniform in CFD vs. slightly non-uniform in experiment) were assessed and found to have negligible effect on the RH QoI based on a sensitivity test. Scoped out from formal equivalency analysis at Gradation 1, with documented qualitative assessment supporting adequacy."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-hemolysis-not-accepted-2026-04",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-board",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CPB hemolysis worst-case identification, MRL 2) is NOT ACCEPTED based on the failure of the Discretization Error credibility factor to meet its required level. The required level for Discretization Error at MRL 2 with high decision consequence and a hemolysis QoI sensitive to near-wall resolution is Gradation 3. The achieved level is Gradation 2, as the mesh refinement study produced a GCI of 8.3% for the primary QoI (relative hemolysis index), exceeding the 5% asymptotic convergence threshold required for Gradation 3, and the observed order of convergence (p=1.4) indicates the solution has not entered the asymptotic regime on the meshes tested. All other assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels: Software Quality Assurance (required 2, achieved 2), Numerical Code Verification (required 2, achieved 2), Test Conditions (required 2, achieved 3), Output Comparison (required 2, achieved 2), Relevance of QoI (required 2, achieved 3), and Relevance of Validation Activities (required 2, achieved 2). Six factors were appropriately scoped out with documented rationale consistent with MRL 2 requirements. The path to acceptance requires: (1) generation of a fourth, further-refined mesh (target >25M cells) to demonstrate asymptotic convergence with GCI < 5% for the RH QoI, or (2) application of Richardson extrapolation with demonstrated p >= 1.8 on three meshes in the asymptotic regime, and (3) re-execution of production hemolysis predictions on the mesh demonstrating asymptotic convergence. Upon remediation, the Discretization Error factor should be re-assessed and the credibility package resubmitted for review.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
